Okay, so from what I've read, Terry Schiavo was a Florida woman who suffered a heart attack in 1990, which led to severe brain damage. She fell into a persistent vegetative state (PVS) and was dependent on medical equipment for her survival, specifically a feeding tube.

The main issue in her case was whether to keep her on life support, particularly the feeding tube, or to remove it, effectively ending her life. Her husband, Michael Schiavo, argued that Terry had previously expressed a desire not to be kept alive in such a condition, while her parents disagreed and wanted to keep her alive as long as possible.

This led to a lengthy legal battle that went all the way to the Supreme Court and even involved intervention by the Florida state government and former President George W. Bush. The case raised significant ethical, legal, and moral questions about end-of-life care, patient autonomy, and the role of family members and the courts in making life-and-death decisions.

